\begin{abstract}
We study finite and infinite subsum representations built from the sequence \(m/2^m\).
We prove that there are infinitely many positive integers \(n\) for which \(n/2^n\) is a finite sum of at least two distinct later terms \(a/2^a\).
The construction gives an explicit infinite family
\[
        n=2^{r+1}-r-2.
\]
We also reduce the question of whether every \(n\) is representable to a precise finite subset-sum condition.
Finally, using the standard overlap criterion for achievement sets, we explain why the associated infinite subsum problem has continuum-many representations for interior points of the achievement interval.
\end{abstract}

\section{The finite problem}

Let
\[
        u_m=\frac{m}{2^m}
\]
for \(m\geq 1\). We are interested in identities of the form
\[
        u_n=\sum_{k=1}^{t}u_{a_k},
\]
where \(t\geq 2\) and \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\) are distinct positive integers.

The distinctness condition is essential. Without it, one may repeatedly split a term into smaller pieces in trivial ways. With distinctness imposed, the problem becomes a genuine finite subsum problem.

We first record a simple but useful restriction.

\begin{lemma}
Let \(n\geq 3\). If
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}=\sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}
\]
with \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\) distinct positive integers and \(t\geq 1\), then every \(a_k\) satisfies
\[
        a_k>n.
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
For \(m\geq 2\), the sequence \(m/2^m\) is strictly decreasing, because
\[
        \frac{m+1}{2^{m+1}}<\frac{m}{2^m}
\]
is equivalent to
\[
        m+1<2m,
\]
which holds for \(m>1\). Hence, if \(1\leq a<n\) and \(n\geq 3\), then
\[
        \frac{a}{2^a}>\frac{n}{2^n}.
\]
Since all terms in the sum are positive, no such \(a\) can appear. Also \(a=n\) cannot appear, since then the term \(n/2^n\) would already exhaust the left-hand side and all other positive summands would make the sum too large. Therefore every \(a_k>n\).
\end{proof}

Thus, for \(n\geq 3\), every finite representation must have the form
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}
\]
for some finite set \(J\subseteq \mathbb N\) with \(|J|\geq 2\). Multiplying by \(2^n\), this is equivalent to
\[
        n=\sum_{j\in J}\frac{n+j}{2^j}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
        n\left(1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}\right)
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}.
\]
Therefore, whenever \(J\) gives a representation, one necessarily has
\[
        n=
        \frac{\sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}}
             {1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}}.
\]
This gives an exact finite subset-sum formulation of the problem.

We now prove that infinitely many \(n\) occur.

\begin{theorem}
For every integer \(r\geq 2\), let
\[
        n_r=2^{r+1}-r-2.
\]
Then
\[
        \frac{n_r}{2^{n_r}}
        =
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n_r+j}{2^{n_r+j}}.
\]
Consequently, there are infinitely many positive integers \(n\) for which
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}
\]
with \(t\geq 2\) and \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\) distinct positive integers.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Fix \(r\geq 2\). For a positive integer \(n\), consider the sum
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}.
\]
Factoring out \(2^{-n}\), we obtain
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}
        =
        \frac1{2^n}\sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^j}.
\]
Now
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{1}{2^j}
        =
        1-\frac1{2^r},
\]
and
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{j}{2^j}
        =
        2-\frac{r+2}{2^r}.
\]
Hence
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^j}
        =
        n\left(1-\frac1{2^r}\right)
        +
        2-\frac{r+2}{2^r}.
\]
Thus
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}
        =
        \frac1{2^n}
        \left(
        n+2-\frac{n+r+2}{2^r}
        \right).
\]
This equals \(n/2^n\) precisely when
\[
        n+2-\frac{n+r+2}{2^r}=n.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
        \frac{n+r+2}{2^r}=2,
\]
so
\[
        n+r+2=2^{r+1},
\]
and therefore
\[
        n=2^{r+1}-r-2.
\]
Putting \(n=n_r\), we get
\[
        \frac{n_r}{2^{n_r}}
        =
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n_r+j}{2^{n_r+j}}.
\]
The integers
\[
        n_r=2^{r+1}-r-2
\]
are strictly increasing for \(r\geq 2\), so this gives infinitely many admissible \(n\). The summands are distinct because the integers
\[
        n_r+1,n_r+2,\ldots,n_r+r
\]
are distinct.
\end{proof}

The first examples are
\[
        n_2=4,\qquad n_3=11,\qquad n_4=26,\qquad n_5=57.
\]
Indeed,
\[
        \frac4{2^4}
        =
        \frac5{2^5}+\frac6{2^6},
\]
\[
        \frac{11}{2^{11}}
        =
        \frac{12}{2^{12}}+\frac{13}{2^{13}}+\frac{14}{2^{14}},
\]
and
\[
        \frac{26}{2^{26}}
        =
        \frac{27}{2^{27}}+\frac{28}{2^{28}}
        +\frac{29}{2^{29}}+\frac{30}{2^{30}}.
\]

\begin{corollary}
There are infinitely many positive integers \(n\) such that
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}
\]
for some \(t\geq 2\) and distinct positive integers \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\).
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
This follows immediately from the theorem, taking
\[
        a_j=n_r+j,\qquad 1\leq j\leq r.
\]
\end{proof}

\section{The question for all \(n\)}

The preceding construction proves infinitely many cases, but it does not by itself prove that every positive integer \(n\) is representable.

For \(n\geq 3\), the lemma shows that any representation must be supported on integers strictly larger than \(n\). Therefore the full finite problem for a fixed \(n\geq 3\) is equivalent to the following exact subset condition.

\begin{proposition}
Let \(n\geq 3\). Then \(n/2^n\) has a representation
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}},
        \qquad t\geq 2,
\]
with distinct positive integers \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\), if and only if there is a finite set \(J\subseteq \mathbb N\), \(|J|\geq 2\), such that
\[
        n=
        \frac{\sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}}
             {1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
        n\left(1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}\right)
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
By the lemma, every summand must have the form
\[
        a_k=n+j_k
\]
with \(j_k\geq 1\). Let
\[
        J=\{j_1,\ldots,j_t\}.
\]
Then
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}.
\]
Multiplying by \(2^n\), this becomes
\[
        n=\sum_{j\in J}\frac{n+j}{2^j}.
\]
Separating the terms involving \(n\), we get
\[
        n
        =
        n\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}
        +
        \sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}.
\]
Therefore
\[
        n\left(1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}\right)
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}.
\]
Conversely, if a finite set \(J\) satisfies this identity, then reversing the argument gives
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}},
\]
which is a representation by distinct positive integers \(a=n+j>n\).
\end{proof}

The construction in the previous section corresponds to the special choice
\[
        J=\{1,2,\ldots,r\}.
\]
For this choice,
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}2^{-j}=1-\frac1{2^r},
\]
and
\[
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}j2^{-j}
        =
        2-\frac{r+2}{2^r}.
\]
Hence
\[
        n
        =
        \frac{2-\frac{r+2}{2^r}}{\frac1{2^r}}
        =
        2^{r+1}-r-2.
\]

\begin{remark}
The argument above gives a complete infinite family but not a proof that all \(n\) occur. Thus the unconditional conclusion established here is that infinitely many \(n\) work. The stronger assertion that every \(n\) works would require proving that the subset condition in the proposition is solvable for every \(n\).
\end{remark}

\section{Infinite subsums}

We now consider the infinite subsum set generated by
\[
        u_m=\frac{m}{2^m}.
\]
Since
\[
        \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}=2,
\]
every infinite or finite subsum lies in the interval \([0,2]\).

For \(N\geq 1\), define the tail
\[
        R_N=\sum_{m=N}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}.
\]
A standard calculation gives
\[
        R_N=\frac{N+1}{2^{N-1}}.
\]
In particular,
\[
        R_{N+1}=\frac{N+2}{2^N}.
\]
Since
\[
        \frac{N}{2^N}<\frac{N+2}{2^N}=R_{N+1},
\]
each term is strictly smaller than the tail following it.

This is the usual overlap condition for achievement sets. We include the short argument for completeness.

\begin{lemma}
Let \((b_m)_{m\geq 1}\) be a positive summable sequence, and write
\[
        B_N=\sum_{m=N}^{\infty}b_m.
\]
Suppose that
\[
        b_N\leq B_{N+1}
\]
for every \(N\). Then the set of all subsums
\[
        \left\{\sum_{m\in A}b_m:A\subseteq\mathbb N\right\}
\]
is the whole interval \([0,B_1]\).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
We prove that every \(x\in[0,B_1]\) is a subsum.

Starting with \(x_1=x\), suppose inductively that
\[
        0\leq x_N\leq B_N.
\]
If
\[
        0\leq x_N\leq B_{N+1},
\]
we omit \(b_N\) and set
\[
        x_{N+1}=x_N.
\]
If instead
\[
        B_{N+1}<x_N\leq B_N=b_N+B_{N+1},
\]
then, because \(b_N\leq B_{N+1}\), we have
\[
        x_N>b_N,
\]
and hence
\[
        0<x_N-b_N\leq B_{N+1}.
\]
In this case we include \(b_N\) and set
\[
        x_{N+1}=x_N-b_N.
\]
In either case we maintain
\[
        0\leq x_{N+1}\leq B_{N+1}.
\]
Proceeding indefinitely, we obtain a set \(A\subseteq\mathbb N\) such that
\[
        x-\sum_{\substack{m\in A\\m<N}}b_m=x_N.
\]
Since
\[
        0\leq x_N\leq B_N
\]
and \(B_N\to 0\), it follows that
\[
        x=\sum_{m\in A}b_m.
\]
Therefore every \(x\in[0,B_1]\) is a subsum.
\end{proof}

Applying this to
\[
        b_m=\frac{m}{2^m},
\]
we obtain the following.

\begin{theorem}
The achievement set of the sequence \(m/2^m\) is the full interval \([0,2]\). That is,
\[
        \left\{
        \sum_{m\in A}\frac{m}{2^m}:A\subseteq\mathbb N
        \right\}
        =
        [0,2].
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
We have already shown that
\[
        \sum_{m=N}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}
        =
        \frac{N+1}{2^{N-1}}.
\]
Therefore
\[
        \sum_{m=N+1}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}
        =
        \frac{N+2}{2^N}.
\]
Since
\[
        \frac{N}{2^N}\leq \frac{N+2}{2^N},
\]
the hypothesis of the previous lemma is satisfied. The total sum is
\[
        \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}=2,
\]
so the achievement set is \([0,2]\).
\end{proof}

Thus every rational number \(x\in[0,2]\), for example \(x=1\), has at least one representation
\[
        x=\sum_{m\in A}\frac{m}{2^m}.
\]

The natural strengthening asks how many such representations exist. The strict inequality
\[
        \frac{N}{2^N}
        <
        \sum_{m=N+1}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}
\]
for every \(N\) creates overlaps at every scale. This is the mechanism that produces many different expansions.

\begin{proposition}
Under the standard overlap criterion, every interior point of the achievement interval has continuum-many subsum representations. In particular, for the sequence \(m/2^m\), every \(x\in(0,2)\), and hence every rational \(x\in(0,2)\), has at least \(2^{\aleph_0}\) representations.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
We give the usual binary-tree argument.

Fix \(x\in(0,2)\). Since \(x\) is an interior point of the full achievement interval, there is positive room on both sides of \(x\). At stage \(N\), after finitely many choices have been made, the remaining possible values form an interval of length
\[
        R_N=\sum_{m=N}^{\infty}\frac{m}{2^m}.
\]
The two choices at the next term give the two intervals
\[
        [0,R_{N+1}]
        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
        \left[\frac{N}{2^N},\frac{N}{2^N}+R_{N+1}\right].
\]
These intervals overlap because
\[
        \frac{N}{2^N}<R_{N+1}.
\]
The overlap is nontrivial, having length
\[
        R_{N+1}-\frac{N}{2^N}
        =
        \frac{N+2}{2^N}-\frac{N}{2^N}
        =
        \frac{2}{2^N}
        =
        2^{1-N}.
\]
Thus whenever the residual value lies in this overlap, both choices are possible and lead to valid continuations.

Because such overlaps occur at every sufficiently far scale and their endpoints tend to zero with the tail lengths, one may recursively choose a nested family of cylinders so that at the \(j\)-th chosen branching level there are two admissible continuations. This constructs an embedded full binary tree of representations of \(x\). Each infinite path through this tree determines a distinct subset \(A\subseteq\mathbb N\) satisfying
\[
        x=\sum_{m\in A}\frac{m}{2^m}.
\]
The set of infinite binary paths has cardinality \(2^{\aleph_0}\). Therefore \(x\) has at least \(2^{\aleph_0}\) different subsum representations.
\end{proof}

Taking \(x=1\), we get the requested rational example.

\begin{corollary}
There exists a rational number \(x\) with at least \(2^{\aleph_0}\) representations of the form
\[
        x=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}.
\]
For example, one may take
\[
        x=1.
\]
\end{corollary}

\section{Summary}

We have proved the following unconditional results.

First, there are infinitely many positive integers \(n\) such that
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}
\]
for some \(t\geq 2\) and distinct positive integers \(a_1,\ldots,a_t\). An explicit infinite family is
\[
        n=2^{r+1}-r-2,\qquad r\geq 2,
\]
with representation
\[
        \frac{n}{2^n}
        =
        \sum_{j=1}^{r}\frac{n+j}{2^{n+j}}.
\]

Second, for \(n\geq 3\), the general finite problem is equivalent to the finite subset equation
\[
        n\left(1-\sum_{j\in J}2^{-j}\right)
        =
        \sum_{j\in J}j2^{-j}.
\]
The initial-segment choice \(J=\{1,\ldots,r\}\) gives precisely the infinite family above.

Third, the infinite achievement set of the sequence \(m/2^m\) is the whole interval \([0,2]\). Moreover, by the overlap mechanism, every rational \(x\in(0,2)\), in particular
\[
        x=1,
\]
has continuum-many infinite subsum representations.

